Additional case details were reported as follows: The patient reported case for herself. After receiving 2nd dose of Shingrix vaccine patient had quite a robust immune response, that included temperature peaked at 101.7, and had all the usual fever symptoms, including achy joints, sensitive skin, tremendous headache, and chills. Additionally, patient experienced redness, swelling, and pain at the injection site, followed a few days later by itchiness. Two days after the vaccination patient also experienced a reactive axillary lymph node, with it being larger than a golf ball and visible through her skin, and which was painful. The size of the lymph node had decreased to less than pea sized, and although patient could feel it, it was no longer visible. SYMPTOM_TEXT: Approximately 10 minutes after receiving the Moderna vaccine, this writer was called to the patient room by other staff.  The patient was extremely confused and not speaking to anyone.  He was gazing to the left and not making eye contact with this writer, who was loudly talking to the patient.  Multiple attempts were made to get the patient's attention with no success.  The patient then began to involuntarily raise his bent left arm in front of his face and then back down to his side.  In this writer's opinion, the patient was having a silent seizure.  This writer sat with the patient, who became aware approximately 15 seconds later.  He was able to answer questions and was quickly reoriented.  At this point this writer had the staff call 911 for further evaluation.  After answering basic questions appropriately., this writer gathered vital signs on the patient .  The first set of vitals were:   bp 88/48, pulse 60, respirations 14/min, oxygen saturation 93% on room air, temp 98.5.  After small conversation with the patient, another set of vitals were taken:   bp 94/70, pulse 68, respirations 15/min, oxygen saturation 95% on room air, temp 98.8.  We then had the patient drink some water, then had him lie down in the patient room until EMS arrived.  By the time they arrived, the patient was completed reoriented and laughing with office staff.  EMS evaluated the patient and deemed him safe to go home with his friend driving.  This writer walked the patient to the car to assess balance and coordination.  This writer informed the patient and his friend to call 911 if symptoms returned.  The patient agreed.
OTHER_MEDS: Patient is prescribed Abilify and Effexor.
HISTORY: Major depressive disorder; Generalized anxiety disorder
PRIOR_VAX: tetanus shot

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient received vaccine at ~3:10pm  was instructed to wait 15 minutes based on the answers she gave on vaccination questionnaire form. Patient indicated on form no allergies and that she she had no prescription for  an Epipen. Patient and her husband approached pharmacy counter at ~3:50pm after having received their vaccines , they  had been shopping in the store beyond  15 minute wait time, asking  to speak with pharmacist. Upon speaking with patient, patient stated " I do not know if this is all in my head but I am starting to fill itchy all over and I have a burning feeling all over my body." Patient stated I am not swelling anywhere and I am not red or blotchy anywhere. I asked patient if her tongue felt funny or like it was swelling or if she was having difficulty breathing or light headed. She stated no. Patient did not appear to have any swelling and  was have no difficulty breathing. I asked patient about allergies even though consent form said no allergies . Patient stated that she did have allergies to bees and had an anaphylaxis reaction before to bees and that she also carries Epipen. She stated she also had allergies to other medications. I recommended that patient have seat in pharmacy vaccine area for me to closely monitor her for 30 minutes. Patient agreed. I monitored patient very closely for 30 minutes and  checked on patient every 5 minutes and took  patients vitals at ~4pm and again at ~4:10pm . Vitals were fine and within normal limits of patient stated usual vitals. Patient stated she took blood pressure medications. Informed patient that we did have Benadryl or hydroxyzine on had if she would like me to adminster a dose per our vaccine protocol. Patient stated no as symptoms were beginning to improve. Asked patient if she would like for me to call EMS to have her checked out. Patient stated no. As the time past patient stated she was not as itchy and the burning feeling wasn't as bad. At 4:25pm, after 30+ minute monitoring period,  informed patient it had now been 30 minutes, patient stated she felt like she was ok and was feeling better. She stated itching had improved and burning feeling improved. Patient asked about taking a benadryl at home and stated that would be fine. Informed patient that if symptoms changed or got  worse at all to be sure to follow up with ER  or PCP depending on severity. Patient husband was with her at the appointment and he was the person driving her home and would be with her once she got home. Patient left pharmacy after symptom improvement and symptoms never got worse than initially presentation.
ALLERGIES: Patient indicated on Pharmacy assessment and  vaccination questionnaire filled out prior to receiving 2nd dose of vaccine-  NO allergies to vaccine, component of vaccines, polyethylene glycol and/or NO prescription for Epinephrine pen for severe allergic reaction. Patient stayed in store past her required 15 minute waiting period per answer she gave on questionnaire and shopped  and came up to pharmacy counter  after about 30minutes after having vaccine saying she  felt itchy all over and like her insides were on fire. Per vaccination questionnaire she indicated no allergies but  at this  time directly asked patient  if she had allergies to anything or ever had anaphylactic reaction she stated yes to but had answer no on questionnaire. Patient stated allergic to bees and carries Epipen with her and stated that she has allergy to different drugs

50 year old male with history of allergic rhinitis, currently on AIT, presents for follow up. Since last seen he initiated AIT in December 2020 and reports he had tolerated his AIT injections without large local or systemic reactions until yesterday, 16 Mar, when he received his first maintenance dose. Within minutes of receiving his dose he developed shortness of breath, dizziness/altered level of consciousness resulting in collapse, and was noted to be hypoxic. He was treated with IM epinephrine with initial improvement but subsequently again developed shortness of breath, cough and altered level of consciousness. He received his second dose of IM epinephrine and a dose of IM Benadryl with transient improvement, but again developed shortness of breath, cough and altered level of consciousness followed by nausea and vomiting. He was noted to be hypotensive and hypoxic despite these interventions so a third dose of IM epinephrine and IV fluids were administered. He was transferred by ambulance to ER where he was given IV solumedrol, monitored, and admitted to the ICU overnight for observation. He reports fever (Tmax 101 F) last night in the ICU. He endorses he took his Allegra prior to his AIT dose and did not exercise. Of note, on 15 Mar he received his second mRNA COVID19 vaccine.

On 11 Mar 2021 at 11:00 am (23.5 hours post vaccine) I had a mild headache and significant dizziness. I had to leave my work desk. This lasted for approximately 2 hours and then "lifted" and I went back to work.  At 4:00pm, about 5 hours later (28.5 hours post vaccine) I felt a total lack of concentration, extreme fatigue, and dizziness. I should have left my desk but had work I needed to complete. This episode also lasted for about 2 hours and then I felt pretty normal again. The following day, on 12 Mar 2021, at 5:00 pm (53.5 hours post vaccine) I had what I described to my sister as  crazy dizziness and extreme lethargy. This lasted for 2-3 hours, I was able to go out with my husband to a store, but was not able to drive. I also experience two days where I had a metallic taste in my mouth. It was not overwhelming, and since I'm sensitive to odors and chemicals anyway I just assumed that there was something in my home I was exposed to, even though that had never happened to me before in my home. This probably occurred on day 3 & 4  post vaccine (13 Mar 2021 and 14 Mar 2021) but I did not annotate the details. I am very suspicious this was also related to the vaccine. As I think about my past few days, especially while at work, I think I am having a harder time than normal concentrating, although at times I have perfect clarity and feel normal.

Passed away; Asthma attack; Tightness in chest; Couldn't breathe; Felt like a panic attack; Resting HR was 145 bpm; Shortness of breath/ winded going up and down stairs; Fever of 100.2 F; Headache came in waves; Extremelynumb mouth and tongue; Felt very dehydrated; Body aches and pains; A spontaneous report was received from a consumer, concerning himself, a 33 years old male patient who received Moderna's Covid-19 Vaccine (mRNA-1273) and experienced extremely numb mouth and tongue, felt very dehydrated, body aches and pains, asthma attack, tightness in chest, couldn't breathe, felt like a panic attack, resting heart rate was 145 bpm, shortness of breath/ winded going up and down stairs, passed away, headache came in waves, fever of 100.2 f.  The patient's medical history reported included asthma in child. Concomitant medications were not reported.   On 06 Jan 2021 at 11:50 AM, the patient received their first dose of two planned doses of mRNA-1273 (Batch number: unknown) intramuscularly in the left upper arm for prophylaxis of COVID-19 infection.   On 06 Jan 2021 (Wednesday), in less than 12 hours after vaccination, patient had an extremely numb tongue and mouth, felt very dehydrated with body aches and pains and also headache that came in waves. On 07 Jan 2020, he had what he would call an asthma attack (he had asthma as a child). SYMPTOM_TEXT: Initial information received on 13-Mar-2021 regarding an unsolicited valid serious literature full article case from another health care professional.   A literature article:  This case is linked to cases 2021SA091226, 2021SA091252, 2021SA091271, 2021SA091286, 2021SA091303, 2021SA091334, 2021SA091349, 2021SA091366, 2021SA091398, 2021SA091448, 2021SA091489, 2021SA091516, 2021SA091556, 2021SA091604, 2021SA091690, 2021SA091745, 2021SA091782, 2021SA091798, 2021SA091833, 2021SA091855 and 2021SA091879. (Same Literature article)  Abstract: On October 7, 2016, the Food and Drug Administration approved recombinant hemagglutinin quadrivalent influenza vaccine (RIV4) (Spodoptera frugiperda cell line; Flublok Quadrivalent) for active immunization for the prevention of influenza disease in individuals 18 years of age and older. Clinical trials did not reveal any major differences in adverse events or serious adverse events following Flublok Quadrivalent versus standard dose quadrivalent inactivated influenza vaccine. To improve our understanding of the safety profile of this vaccine, we reviewed and summarized adverse event reports after Flublok Quadrivalent administration to the vaccine adverse event reporting system (VAERS). Through June 30, 2020, VAERS received 849 reports after RIV4 vaccination. The vast majority (810; 95%) were nonserious. Among serious events, there were 10 cases of Guillain-Barre syndrome, including 5 people who required mechanical ventilation and 2 people who died. Many allergic reactions were reported as non-serious, but required interventions to treat a life-threatening event, example: epinephrine, nebulizers, albuterol, glucocorticoids, and supplemental oxygen. Two people experienced a positive rechallenge (which are allergic reactions after repeated vaccination with RIV4), including a person who despite premedication with antihistamines developed respiratory difficulties, required epinephrine, and was transported to the emergency department. The occurrence of anaphylaxis and other allergic reactions in some individuals may reflect an underlying predisposition to atopy that may manifest itself after an exposure to any drug or vaccine and does not necessarily suggest that Flublok Quadrivalent is particularly allergenic. Post marketing safety surveillance will continue to be vital for understanding the benefits and risks of quadrivalent recombinant influenza vaccine.  This case involves a 65 years old female patient who experienced pulmonary abscess (lung abscess), intraparenchymal hemorrhage (cerebral haemorrhage), 60 to 70 percent stenosis of the coronary arteries (coronary artery stenosis), pulseless electrical activity, cardiogenic shock, aspiration event (aspiration) and takotsubo cardiomyopathy (stress cardiomyopathy), after she received INFLUENZA QUADRIVALENT RECOMBINANT VACCINE [FLUBLOK QIV].  Past medical treatment, vaccination, family history and concomitant medication were not reported.  At the time of the event, the patient had ongoing medical history of chronic obstructive pulmonary disease, coronary artery disease, hypothyroidism, depression, gastroesophageal reflux disease and hepatic cirrhosis.  On an unknown date, the patient received a dose of suspect INFLUENZA QUADRIVALENT RECOMBINANT VACCINE [batch number, expiry date and other dosing details were not reported] for prophylactic vaccination.  On an unknown date, the patient developed a serious pulseless electrical activity, takotsubo cardiomyopathy (stress cardiomyopathy), cardiogenic shock, aspiration event (aspiration), intraparenchymal hemorrhage (cerebral haemorrhage) and pulmonary abscess (lung abscess), 7 weeks following the administration of INFLUENZA QUADRIVALENT RECOMBINANT VACCINE.   The patient was resuscitated, hospitalized on an unknown date for the reported events and stabilized.  On an unknown date, the patient developed a serious 60 to 70 percent stenosis of the coronary arteries (coronary artery stenosis), (unknown latency) following the administration of INFLUENZA QUADRIVALENT RECOMBINANT VACCINE and no intervention was performed. Patient was hospitalized during this event.   Relevant laboratory test results included: On an unknown date: Catheterization cardiac- cardiac catheterization revealed 60-70 percent stenosis of the coronary arteries.  It was not reported if the patient received any corrective treatment.  At the time of reporting, event outcome was not reported for all the reported events.   There will be no information available on the batch number for this case.; Sender's Comments: This case involved a 65 years old female patient who presented with coronary artery stenosis, lung abscess, cerebral haemorrhage, pulseless electrical activity, cardiogenic shock, aspiration and stress cardiomyopathy after the administration of FLUBLOK QIV. Time of onset was unknown for coronary artery stenosis and compatible for remaining reported events. At the time of the event, the patient had ongoing chronic obstructive pulmonary disease, coronary artery disease, hypothyroidism, depression, gastroesophageal reflux disease and hepatic cirrhosis. Cardiac catheterization was performed which revealed serious 60-70% stenosis of the coronary arteries. Further information regarding previous vaccination/treatment and tolerance, other laboratory investigations excluding alternative etiologies for the reported event are needed to fully assess this case. Based upon the reported information, the role of the suspect vaccine cannot be assessed.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I had long term Covid symptoms from early February 2020 to late February 2021 including, intense concussion like brain fog for months, coughing for months, problems with my fingers seizing up and twitching uncontrollably, and extreme exhaustion for months. I had finally started to feel Covid free, except for some problems with my left hand, by end of February 2021. I got the first dose and about 45 minutes or so later the exhaustion came back suddenly - like someone removed all my batteries - and I started having trouble talking, thinking, remembering. Reading and writing work, but talking is difficult. My hands feel swollen and lacking dexterity and strength. I had an odd headache in the middle of the night (on day 2) with some sharp pain that kind of seeped around my scalp. I thought at first I had been stung by a bee and it went away as quickly as it came. But then the pain would suddenly appear on another part of my scalp. There was a tingling/seeping/spreading out feeling just before it would disappear. I woke up the next morning with a more normal headache, took IBU and CBD gummies, ate breakfast and it?s gone. I feel like all I can do is lay in bed and stare at the wall. This is exactly as I felt when I had Covid (though without finger seizures and coughing). I find myself coming to tears with a fear that it won?t ever go away or I?ve brought it on again by getting the vaccine.

I had my second COVID shot at 36 weeks, 6 days pregnant. My due date is April 16. I had no problems immediately after the shot except soreness in my arm. However, that night, I started to feel groggy. When I woke up the next morning my body was achy and I felt very fatigued. A few hours later I started vomiting and had diarrhea. My stomach was cramping. I felt like I had a fever but couldn't find a thermometer to check on that. It felt like I had some kind of stomach virus. I did have some kind of stomach bug about three weeks ago that made me so dehydrated I had an IV in the hospital. For that illness I was prescribed diphenoxylate-atropine 2.5-0.025 mg to take at home. I still had some of that medicine left, so I took one of those pills hoping to stop my diarrhea. I didn't want dehydration or cramping to affect my pregnancy. The medicine did stop my diarrhea and vomiting, but I still had all the other symptoms until the middle of the night. I woke up feeling better.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Chills, vomiting, severe headache, extremely tired

I vaccinated the pt who stated he only had a sore arm with the first vaccine and no other reaction and that he had never had any kind of severe reaction to drugs, vaccines, or foods.  Approximately 5-10 minutes after vaccinating Client, I was informed that his top lip was swelling as he sat in our Waiting Area.  I immediately went to check on him and observed visible swelling of the middle of his top lip.  I asked if he had noticed any other swelling, trouble swallowing, or breathing, to which he replied he did not.  I then when to check with the pharmacist running the clinic to verify the best way to proceed.  I was prepared with an Epipen a few feet away from pt to use if needed. Another pharmacist, brought over an ice pack. Pharmacist again questioned the pt who affirmed he had no other symptoms and that the swelling did not appear to be spreading.  We offered to call 911 and the pt declined, insisting that we not make a fuss.  We insisted that we wanted to make sure he did not have any trouble breathing or any other reaction and to sit for 30 minutes of observation.  Pt accepted the ice pack and reluctantly agreed to sit for "a while".  I sat with the pt monitoring him closely for about 30 minutes and engaged him in conversation.  Pt had no issues breathing or speaking and repeatedly stated that it was not itchy or painful and the swelling had receded minimally after 30 minutes.  He experienced no other symptoms, but was tired and wanted to go home,  He explained that he had his colon removed this past Monday and was in some discomfort and was very tired.  The patient was eager to leave and again declined further medical treatment.  I provided the patient with generic benadryl tablets since he he did not have any at home.  I instructed him to go home, take 2 tablets with a big glass of water, and take his nap. I asked if I could call him later this afternoon to follow-up with him and he approved.  I told him that I would report the incident here.  I also told him that if his symptoms worsened and if he had any trouble breathing to call 911.  The patient then left the Waiting Area.
CUR_ILL: colon cancer, removal of colon, enlarged prostate
HISTORY: HX OF COLON CANCER, ENLARGED PROSTATE

While staffing observation, I (EMT) observed the patient to appear to be short of breath. The patient had removed her mask and was breathing rapidly with accessory muscle usage. I escorted the patient to the EMS Exam Room and called for my partner ( Paramedic) to assist me. While in the exam room we obtained a set of vitals. The patients vitals at 1545 were P:132, BP:160/90, Resp: 20, SpO2 91% on RA. After examining the patient, she stated that she had a history of MACs and was being treated for that at Clinic. The patent also stated that she had a history of cardiac problems but was unable to elaborate on what they were. After 15 minutes the patient was evaluated---

Patient reported no to having prior history of fainting or dizziness after receiving vaccine. Vaccine was administered at approximately 9:04 am and patient's boyfriend was administered at approximately 9:08. Upon return to his seat beside her at approximately 9:10 am, he noticed she was losing color and going limp. He called for help, and I assisted. The pharmacy team sent a Code White on the radio and several members of management responded to check on the scene. We moved the patient to the floor and applied ice packs to the neck and chest and removed her face mask for better circulation. The patient was wearing a thick sweatshirt so we attempted to increase air flow around her head and neck to cool her down as she was visibly sweating. The patient never lost consciousness or breathing and her pulse was always palpable. By 9:20 am, we had moved the patient from the floor to a sitting position then to a chair and provided her with a cold bottle of water and continued one ice pack on her neck. She stayed seated until 9:40 (34 minutes after her injection). She denied the need for an ambulance transport as she had her boyfriend here who could drive her.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Between 10 and 15 minutes after receiving the vaccine, I felt like someone had thumped me in the chest over my left breast. I tried to breathe deeply, and I started to feel light headed. I didn't tell anyone, I was let go after 15 minutes. I sat in my car about 5 minutes and then decided I was worse. I was weak and shaky and light headed, my top lip was fuzzy feeling. I didn't feel like there was a blockage in my airway but I felt like I was having trouble getting my rib cage to expand so I could breathe. I went back in and was sat down, I was evaluated. Paramedics were called, by time they came I was lightheaded and I was foggy brained. I couldn't respond easily. My BP was 165/99 and my heart rate was 98. my O2 was fine but by that time I felt like I had to work hard to get a deep breath. I was feeling worse quickly. I was taken to the ER in a wheelchair. I was put in a bed and hooked me up to monitors. I was left alone for a while. When the dr came in he checked me out and listen to my lungs. I had a hard time getting my lungs to expand. Doctor ordered a blood sugar test and it was below 100. Chest x-ray, EKG and blood work. He told me later that everything was normal. I was there for 2 hours before I felt like I could go home. I didn't receive any medication. I was able to breathe easier by time I left the hospital. I was thinking more clearly as well. The next day I was still feeling shaky and weak. I went to my PCP on friday and I was feeling normal by then.
OTHER_MEDS: Levothyroxine, montelukast, arthritis pain relief acetaminophen, glucosamine supplement, womens multivitamin, fibralgia, malic acid.

I have Covid arm.  Developed a lump over the next several days post vaccine, which got larger over time.  Didn't hurt too much unless I touched it.  Didn't stop me from doing anything I normally do, and I didn't pay much attention to it.  On Day 10 post vaccine, I happened to look at my arm in the mirror after a shower, and noticed a red circular rash at the injection site, about the circumference of a golf ball.  The lump underneath was very warm to the touch, and the spot was still sore if touched.  Kept watching daily.  On Day 12, it was the largest that it had been...the rash was 2 1/2 inches in diameter and still warm and sore.   Had soreness going up into my neck and down towards my elbow.  By Day 14, I noticed that the center of the area was returning to normal skin color, so the rash looked like a big red 'O' now.  Have taken Benadryl the last two nights, and it appears a lot lighter in color today (Day 15 post vaccine).  Lump is still there and still warm, but it seems that the worst is over.  The lump fills my cupped palm, but I can push on it pretty hard now without pain.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I had my vaccine on Saturday and on Monday my platlets were at 16. I was almost hospitalized but, after steroids they improved.

One week after Dose 1, I exercized heavily with my arms.  The next day, my vaccine location was again red, warm, and raised.  There was no rash, as in patients describing "covid arm."  It was not very painful, either.. but I did do a good job keeping my arm mobile for both vaccines.  Two weeks after Dose 1, I got a rash for the first time in my adult life (I'm almost 35 years old).  The rash was localized to be just on my "seat" area... literally.  That took over a week to dissipate, but eventually I didn't notice it.  One week after Dose 2, I woke up with red swollen hands, a swollen rash on the undersides of my forearms, a little on my stomach, and a little rash on just the instep arches of both feet.  The rash was spreading, so I was advised to go to a clinic.  Unfortunately, that clinic didn't do any bloodwork, but they sent me home with scripts for prednisone and famotidine thinking I was having an allergic reaction to the pizza I ate the previous night.  I also got a shot in the butt.  The rash and swelling dissipated by over 50% by the next morning.  However, after a day of work and movement, I realized the rash was still spreading and I was now gaining weight.   It is now 3/26, which is two weeks after receiving the 2nd dose of the Moderna vaccine.  The rash is still spreading around my skin.  I completed my medication and now I am monitoring the rash on my own.  The oldest sites seem to be healing.  It is now contained to my stomach, mostly lower abdomen, around the sides and to the back... also very swollen and itchy (now) in my seat and groin area.
LAB_DATA: n/a, though I will updated this site if I need to seek more urgent medical care.  I may need to get bloodwork done to determine if this is an allergic reaction or a virus.
OTHER_MEDS: Venlafaxine 150mg, Cetirizine 10mg, Vitamin D  50,000mg/wk, Lithium Orotate, Iron

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I received the vaccine at 9:15a and was told to wait 30 min instead of 15 due to my anaphylactic allergy history. At 9:21a, while in the waiting area, I felt a flushing sensation through my body and felt my face grow hot. I got very light-headed even though I was sitting down and thought I was going to be sick, and my heart rate as noted on my watch became elevated. It went from low 70's to high 90's. My throat did not close up and I did take my regular allergy medicine and inhalers prior to the vaccine. After 30 minutes, I went to the facility restroom and noted my face was still red. I called my sister (a hospital doctor) who told me to immediately take Benedryl. After taking Benedryl, I was feeling better after about another hour and the nausea and light-headedness subsided. In total, the symptoms lasted about an hour and 45 minutes. I did not notify staff at Med.Centerl at that time as my throat didn't close but did contact my PCP and now have an appointment scheduled with an allergist at Med. Center for next week and have put my 2nd vaccine on hold until I see the allergist.
LAB_DATA: None yet. I have an appointment with an allergist at the Med. Center on April 8th, 2021.
HISTORY: mild-to-moderate asthma due to dog allergy (and I love dogs so have two); seasonal allergies (pollen, molds, grasses) ; past positive ANA for years with joint pain but not in the past five years; history of acute bacterial endocarditis following severe reaction to nickel in braces on my teeth in childhood (which required open heart surgery later) but no current cardiac condition and have been told by my cardiologist that heart is great (I'm super active and a healthy eater with normal BMI/cholesterol levels and low blood pressure).
ALLERGIES: Celiac's disease (gluten/wheat); allergies to nickel, bananas, peanuts, red dye in clothing (hives), and an anaphylactic allergy to shellfish. Not sure if it's an allergy but had projectile vomiting after ingesting colonoscopy prep drink. No known medication allergies.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I don't know that this has any relation to the vaccine, but felt I should report anyway.  This was just over 24 hours after the second dose. I took my blood pressure at home for my regular tracking purposes.  My BP was 151/113 when I normally run in the neighborhood of 117/68.   My monitor also indicated my heart rate was 96 BPM which is unusually high for me as I normally run in the 50/60's.  I didn't feel bad at all and my only indication came when I did the actual reading.   I did some deep breathing and took my BP again later in the evening and it was down to 143/91.  Checking back on my heart rate trends for March 24, I can see my heart rate had risen to a high of 117 BPM between the hours of 7-8pm and finally returned to my normal range between 11pm and midnight.  From then on during my sleep cycle between Midnight and 7am March 25, my heart rate remained in the 50's as expected.     There are no other issues to report.  Again, I can't say conclusively this was due to the vaccine, but I can't rule it out either.  I thought I should report the information regardless.

"I" in this synopsis: I was noti?ed on 3/2/2021 during the P?zer 1st Dose clinic that Patient wanted to report an issue receiving his vaccine administered by MSN LPN.  I interviewed patient who stated he was injected twice during his vaccine administration. He was concerned that he may have been poked with a dirty needle and then given the actual vaccine. He stated that LPN administered the ?rst syringe when he commented that it burned. He stated LPN told him there wasn't anything in that one and then administered the actual vaccine. Patient showed me his arm where it did, in my opinion, appear there were two needle marks in his deltoid region.  I discussed the issue with LPN. Her story was inconsistent as she repeated what happened. She stated she did not inject the patient twice. She denies using a dirty syringe on the patient and stated she immediately throws her dirty needles in the sharps container.   I interviewed LPN a second time with another person present. LPN initially stated she did not inject patient twice. She later stated that she did poke patient twice: The ?rst time is when patient complained it burned. LPN stated she pulled the needle out and then proceeded to use the same needle and injected the patient with the same needle. I informed nurse that I advised against that practice and that her story had changed from the previous versions. I informed her I was sending her home immediately.

Initial side effects included fatigue, intermittent chills and fever (unmeasured), severe body aches, and injection site pain and soreness.  On day 4, the chills and injection site complaints were gone.  On the night of day 4, I developed a dry cough and throat irritation.  On day 5, my body aches were gone, but I had a low-grade fever all day and developed hives-like spots throughout my body, although they were mild and did not itch.  I lost my appetite.  Fatigue lessoned to tiredness, but the dry cough and throat irritation worsened.  On day 6, my body temperature normalized, at least for the most part.  My cough and throat irritation continued to worsen, and I received a positive COVID-19 antigen test result.  (My PCR test result was negative.)  On the night of day 6, I developed chest discomfort.  On day 7, my symptoms continued, and I also had taste disturbances with certain foods.  On day 9, my appetite improved a little bit, but additional hives-like spots developed.  On day 9, I also re-tested for COVID-19.  Both my antigen and PCR results were negative.  On day 10, my dry cough, throat irritation, and chest discomfort began to fractionally improve, but I suffered some mild body aches again.  Today, on day 12, I am still suffering from a dry cough, throat irritation, and chest discomfort, with decreased appetite.

We

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Received the vaccine shot in the morning of March 24th, as the day wore on the vision in my right eye changed, becoming cloudy and somewhat obscured, it felt like i had some pressure or the right eyeball was swollen a bit,  I had difficulty focusing  close up, difficulty reading. When looking at distant objects, such as a street light, the light source looked like a spiky ring of light.  The vision in the left eye was a bit cloudy but that was gone by the morning of the 25th.  The vision issues in the right eye continued through most of the 25th though the feeling of pressure diminished and the  vision issues also lessened.  The eye/vision is still not completely back to normal on the 26th but is much better.
LAB_DATA: None .  If the vision issue continues for a few more days I'll follow up with an appointment with my drs.

Patient came to public clinic with neighbor to receive COVID vaccine. They received Moderna 006b21a by  NP in their right arm and then a family member showed up at the door stating ?she?s already had it? . Patient had received Pfizer COVID vaccine on 2/3/2021 and 2/24/2021.  Family member states she had a mild reaction after her series, with injection site pain and abdominal discomfort. Patient was monitored for 30 mins without reaction. PCP has been notified and HCP  is aware as well. She has visiting nursing 4 times a day at home and I will follow up with HCP this afternoon for re-eval.  Board of health physician Dr.  notified. Patient and family members present have been counseled on adverse reactions and when to seek medical care. Information will be reviewed with HCP today as well.
CUR_ILL: None disclosed, dementia disclosed by family member

Left arm injection site grew more red, tender, and swollen. 3/26/21 7:00am 99.1 fever and lump grew slightly larger over left collar bone. Left arm still very red, swollen and tender. Approx 2.5 inch diameter circle around injection site.

PRIOR_VAX: Moderna vaccine #1. Swollen red tender injection site for 12 days.

No other AE reported; temperature excursion 11 C for 10 hrs, vaccine administered; This spontaneous report was received from a medical assistant and refers to a 11-year-old male Hispanic patient. There was no information about the patient's concurrent conditions, concomitant therapies or medical history provided. On 02-MAR-2021 (also reported as yesterday), the patient was vaccinated with improperly stored 0.5 ml dose of hpv rl1 6 11 16 18 31 33 45 52 58 vlp vaccine (yeast) (GARDASIL 9) lot # T007035, expiration date 01-MAY-2022 (the route of administration was not reported) for prophylaxis. There was no adverse effect reported. Administered dose of vaccine experienced the temperature excursion of 11 degrees Celsius for 10 hours. Data logger was involved. There were no previous excursions reported.  On 09-MAR-2021, an inbound phone call was received from a medical assistant (MA) who works with nurse practitioner (NP, correspondence contact). The MA was calling in response to the Merck correspondence received in the mail regarding the patient who had received hpv rl1 6 11 16 18 31 33 45 52 58 vlp vaccine (yeast) (GARDASIL 9) vaccinations after the vaccine had undergone a temperature excursion on 16-FEB-2021 for 10 hours. The lot number and expiration date were previously reported. The adverse event follow-up process was reviewed with both the MA and the NP and they verbalized understanding. The MA stated that she was the health care professional (HCP) who administered the vaccines to the four patients listed below. The MA states that she was certified and trained to administer these vaccines. The MA provided patient's age, gender and ethnic group. The MA stated that she would hold onto each letter in case there was additional information to report. Minimal information was obtained on that day, due to the HCPs being "very busy". At the time of the phone call, the patient had not experienced cellulitis, erythema, or swelling at the site of the injection. The vaccine was not available for return.  Additional information is not expected. The patient's concomitant therapies included sterile diluent (MERCK STERILE DILUENT). The patient's concurrent conditions, historical drugs and medical history were not reported.        On an unknown date, the patient was vaccinated with varicella virus vaccine live (oka/merck)(VARIVAX) 0.5 ml, subcutaneously, in the left thigh, Lot # T022314, expiration date 30-JUN-2022 for prophylaxis.     On an unknown date, the child experienced severe localized reactions. The patient had cellulitis at the shot location (Vaccination site cellulitis). All of the reactions were red swollen (Vaccination site swelling) and hot to touch area (Vaccination site warmth). The adverse reaction occurred in the left thigh; 4-6 centimeter wide.   It was reported that the patient sought medical attention and it was unknown whether the patient underwent any laboratory or diagnostic tests.  The reporter informed that he/she has been doing this for 30 years and has never seen anything like it and he/she considered the reaction was coming from an specific lot number of varicella virus vaccine live (oka/merck)(VARIVAX) Lot # T022314, expiration date 30-JUN-2022. Additionally, that the adverse event was not related to the diluent because the same diluent was used for the Measles, Mumps, and Rubella (Wistar RA 27-3) Virus Vaccine, Live (M-M-R II) as was used for the varicella virus vaccine live (oka/merck)(VARIVAX)  and they had not had any adverse reactions involving the Measles, Mumps, and Rubella (Wistar RA 27-3) Virus Vaccine, Live (M-M-R II). The reporter informed they had 3 or 4 unused vials of the varicella virus vaccine live (oka/merck)(VARIVAX) Lot # T022314, expiration date 30-JUN-2022  left to return. It was reported that the varicella virus vaccine live (oka/merck)(VARIVAX) was stored at the recommended range, also reported as Frozen. It did not experience a temperature excursion and the storage temperature was monitored via a data logger. The reporter confirmed there were not any particles or matter in the varicella virus vaccine live (oka/merck)(VARIVAX) vial.  At the time of reporting, the patient was recovering from vaccination site cellulitis, vaccination site warmth and vaccination site swelling. The causal relationship between varicella virus vaccine live (oka/merck)(VARIVAX) and the vaccination site cellulitis, vaccination site warmth and vaccination site swelling was not reported.  This is one of nine reports received from the same reporter.; Sender's Comments:  US-009507513-2103USA006522:

Concurrent medical conditions included heart disorder, polymyalgia rheumatica, cellulitis and atrial fibrillation. Concomitant products included digoxin and prednisone.   On 11th December 2020, the patient received Shingrix. On 11th February 2020, the patient started dupilumab (subcutaneous) 600 mg 4 times daily (600 mg daily). In 2020, the dose was changed to an unknown dose and frequency. On 25th December 2020, 14 days after receiving Shingrix and an unknown time after starting digoxin and Valtrex, the patient experienced shingles, pain, rash and difficulty sleeping. The patient was treated with valaciclovir hydrochloride (Valtrex), bumetanide and pregabalin (Lyrica). Dupilumab was discontinued. On an unknown date, the outcome of the shingles, pain, rash and difficulty sleeping were recovering/resolving.   It was unknown if the reporter considered the shingles, pain, rash and difficulty sleeping to be related to Shingrix.  Additional details were provided as follows: The patient received Shingrix and started with pain on her right side, rash at the right side at waistline from the never at the center of back, because of the pain the patient was not able to sleep and was diagnosed with shingle and most of skin was cleared off with the exception of back of neck and head, which was still itching, while the patient was treated with dupilumab Dupixent delivered via dupilumab pre-filled syringe.  On 25th December 2020, 14 days after the patient experienced shingles, pain, rash and difficulty sleeping. The concomitant medications included Digoxin for Atrial fibrillation and to prevent clog and Prednisone for cellulitis all over. On 11th February 2020, the patient started taking dupilumab injection 600 mg once via subcutaneous route with an unknown strength, batch number and expiry date followed by 300 mg every other week since an unknown date in 2020 via dupilumab pre-filled syringe for atopic dermatitis.  In the COVID19 crisis, the batch number and expiration date were not requested. On 25th February 2020, the patient complained that ankles looked great but they were swollen joint swelling, had swelling in feet, the left worse than right, from the ankles to the toes peripheral swelling and condition aggravated. The reporter would not give up the patient Dupilumab.  On 09th December 2020, the doctor prescribed a Shingrix vaccination and on 11th December 2020 the patient received 1st dose of Shingrix. On unknown date, the doctor advised to temporarily stop Dupilumab. The patient was getting better.  At the time of report, Dupilumab was discontinued.  No additional information available at the time of the report. It was further reported that patient called the program and they told the consumer to wait 24 hours before taking the vaccine, waited 48 hours.  The patient had been off the antiviral medication that was prescribed for 10 days and wondered about resuming dupilumab and did missed the dose that was scheduled on 06th January 2021. On 30 Jan 2021, the patient received her first planned dose of mRNA-1273 (batch number: 007MZ0A) intramuscularly for prophylaxis of COVID-19 infection.   On 27 Feb 2021, she had her second planned dose of mRNA-1273 (batch number: 01021A) intramuscularly on left arm. Soon, she developed itching at injection site down to her toes and left side of the body. She developed painful nodules on shoulders as well as both under arms and it was mentioned that the one on left side was severe.  On 09 Mar 2021, she began experiencing cramps and spasms on her right and left legs. She was diagnosed with blood clots in both legs while in the emergency room  (ER). She was treated with hydroxyzine and apixaban.  The event blood clot in both legs was considered to be medically significant.  The action taken with mRNA-1273 in response to the events injection site itching, itching down to her toes and left side of the body, painful nodules under both arms and shoulders and blood clot in both legs was unknown. 47 year old Gynecologist with PMH of severe MDD, GERD, asthma, referred to the ED by his PCP, after 5 days of gait instability, and about 4 weeks of altered mental status, confusion, short term memory deficits and malaise. ADEM suspected and extensive infectious, inflammatory and neoplastic workup was initiated. CT brain  - reported NAD MRI brain consistent with Acute Diffused Encephalomyelitis and suspected ADEM. MRI cervical spine with evidence of demyelination involving posterior cord. ICU course complicated by new onset of aphasia, partial left frontotemporal seizures, LGIB due to proximal rectal laceration and central diabetes insipidus.  Admitted 3/15/21.  On 3/17 he developed aphasia with right sided facial droop and stroke alert was called. Later on 3/17 he developed GI bleeding and was taken for emergent colonoscopy, from which no significant conclusions could be made due to lack of preparation and subsequent poor visualization. No foreign body was reported. After he continued to have ongoing bleeding, the patient had a sigmoidoscopy, during which the migrated clip could be removed and two new hemostatic clips were placed.  He subsequently developed large volume urine output and nephrology was consulted; the patient was diagnosed with likely diabetes insipidus.  On 3/20 acyclovir was discontinued after HSV PCR was negative. High dose solumedrol for ADEM completed 5 day course 3/21.  VDRL was non reactive. There were no oligoclonal bands. Solumedrol 1g daily was started 3/24/21: MRI showed L>R patchy enhancement and diffusion abnormalities consistent with ADEM. Repeat MRI showed new restricted diffusion of the left superior cortex, bilateral medial temporal lobes and hippocampi, genu of the corpus collosum, and pericallosal white matter, with ddx including status epilepticus, autoimmune encephalitis and infectious encephalitis including herpes simplex.  Completed 5 day course of high dose steroids, 6 days of IVIG and on ongoing PLEX. Neurological improvement noted 3/25
LAB_DATA: - Negative oligoclonal bands ruling out MS. HBV, HCV neagtive.  - CRP, ESR, RPR are normal.  - Added lyme antibodies  - Ongoing B12, folate supplementation ID:  - Elevated white count 13K, mild left shift,fever resolved.  - Urine cultures with coag negative staph. Probably contamination. BCx are negative to date.   - Has intravascular catheters. To be closely monitored for time;line of replacement.  -  LP with no pleocytosis, negative cultures, negative HSV. Serum WNV IgG positive. Not clinically significant.  - Pending lyme antibodies and CSF studies: encephalitis panel (Measle IgG), CJD 14-3-3 antigen.  -  Bcx and repeat urine cultures taken.  - Cont empiric vancomycin and meropenem started on 3/22, until bcx fully resulted..

From provider's note: Patient is a 59yr old female who presents with concerns for left sided facial numbness. Received first dose of Moderna vaccine yesterday, within 30 minutes of administration patient began having numbness to the left side of her face. No issues with breathing or swallowing. Describes as similar to receiving Novocaine at the dentist. It has not worsened or improved over night. Has a history of GBS over 30 years ago. Has not received flu shot because of this. No contraindications to receiving SARS vaccine. No unilateral weakness. No headaches. She does have some discomfort over her injections site, she did receive the injection in her left arm.    Physical Exam: BP 134/97  Pulse 100  Temp 99.2 �F (37.3 �C) (Temporal)  Resp 16  Wt 79.4 kg (175 lb)  SpO2 98%  BMI 28.25 kg/m2|| Physical Exam  Constitutional: She is oriented to person, place, and time and well-developed, well-nourished, and in no distress.  Cardiovascular: Normal rate, regular rhythm and normal heart sounds.  No murmur heard. Pulmonary/Chest: Effort normal and breath sounds normal. No respiratory distress.  Neurological: She is alert and oriented to person, place, and time. She has normal motor skills, normal strength and intact cranial nerves. She displays normal speech. A sensory deficit is present. Gait normal.  **No facial droop, decreased sensation from midline of face along the left side to approximately ear ** Skin: Skin is warm and dry.   Plan: with the almost immediate presentation it is unlikely that vaccine caused reaction, but VAERS report to be completed. Then this past Tuesday (03-23-2021) I went to receive the 2nd Covid-19 Moderna Vaccine at 1:00pm. I felt fine and had no adverse after this vaccination until 8:30pm the same day. At this time I started to have sever  itching and within an hour the itching was over my entire body. It was a mixture of hives and regular pruritus/itching and areas of swelling throughout my body. This lasted all through the night into Wednesday, 03-24-21. Around the same time as the itching started Tuesday night, my Spinal joints, Hip joints, shoulder joints, knee joints, wrist and ankles became severely inflamed and very painful. On a scale of 1-10, 10 being the worst pain, at the highest I was at a 9.    On Wednesday, I went in to my Primary Care for the itching and the pain. My PCP is on vacation this week, so I saw his Colleague. Dr. visibly recognized the redness from the itching all over my body, along with the extreme pain to my joints and gave me a thorough examination. After his examination  he spoke to another physician who stepped in and also gave me an exam. Dr. advised the other Dr. and me of  his initial hesitancy  sending me home, wanting me to be observed overnight at the Hospital. After going to their Emergency Room. They gave me the choice but I truly thought it would go away over the course of the usual 24 hours post Vaccination; I also did not want to be exposed to any virus/sickness I might encounter/pick up in the Hospital due to my lowered immune system because of the rheumatoid arthritis injection Humira I take bi-monthly.. I explained that I was living with my mom, and our residence is 7 minutes from the Hospital, Emergency Room.) I assured both Physicians if it got worse, my mother would take me to the ER. So instead of going to Hospital, they prescribed a Hydrocortisone Cream of  2.5% for the itching, kept me on oral Benadryl and told me to stay hydrated. Also, Dr. said if it wasn?t better and/or worse Thursday(03/25/21)to come back in for re-evaluation. Along with the medications for itching, they prescribed a dose of pain medicine: Tylenol(APAP) #4 - or Acetaminophen with 60mg of Codeine.    Yesterday - Thursday(03-25-2021) I was no better, and had to go back in to the Clinic.  I was seen by Dr., who also believed this reaction to be based on the Humira along with my immune system naturally being lowered due to the AS and RA medication. Dr. examined me, as by yesterday my hands/fingers were hurting as well and itching was not any better. He prescribed Atarax (Hydroxyzine) 50mg Cap to be taken 3 times per day for the awful Pruritis, which has caused me to scratch so badly that I?ve had some bleeding from areas on my body, near the larger joints and spine. And also changed the Tylenol #4 to every 4 hours, basically more often for the pain associated.    Adding the Hydroxyzine for the itch along with the Hydrocortisone, pain medication and time since Tuesday?s final vaccine, has helped a bit. Today, Friday, I am feeling less itchy but still having quite a bit of joint pain, but less than Wednesday or Thursday of this week.  Because of the itching and joint/spine pain I received very little sleep until last evening when I was able to rest and not itch or toss and turn from pain. Hopefully on the mend.
LAB_DATA: Severe swelling and itching; Pain scale. Blood Work to work out other issues that might have caused reaction.

Seven days after vaccine was administered Patient started having symptoms of difficulty breathing, rapid heart rate, and breaking out in a rash all over  his torso and upper arms.  His lips also got quite swollen.  The rash eventually spread down both his legs.  He was taken to the emergency room at Hospital, as he was visiting there at the time.  He was given benadryl, and prednisone once his Covid test came back negative.  Blood work, chest x-ray, CT scan of both stomach and chest, EKG and blood work all came back normal.  His resting heart rate was 120 and above, and he required two liters of oxygen to stay in the mid 90's saturation level.  He spent five days in the hospital before the rash was mostly faded on his torso and his lip swelling had come down.  He was discharged on 3/24/21 with the advice to see his primary care physician, and to be monitored carefully for oxygen saturation and heart rate.  The family could not think of anything he had eaten or come in contact with that would have caused any reaction.  At this time we think it was a reaction to his Janssen vaccine based on all the tests at the hospital coming back normal.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Within an hour of the shot, started feeling dizzy.  Intense fatigue and full body aches set in within 3 hours.  Facial numbness and left-side facial drooping began within 8 hours.  Low fever, chills, heavy heart beat, and intermittent cramps of the abdomen and on the left side (between hip and rib cage) began within 18 hours.  Swollen lymph nodes in the neck and constipation began within 48 hours.  At ~4 days since the first shot, the facial numbness, heavy heart beat, and fatigue persisted, though the drooping became less prominent and the other symptoms have largely resolved.  At ~2 weeks since the first shot, the facial numbness has been constant, but varying in intensity, and the left-side facial drooping has returned multiple times.
LAB_DATA: MRI of the head and blood work were ordered and performed.  Given no prior history with these issues, the timing relative to the administration of the first vaccine shot, and the lack of findings from imaging and blood work, the symptoms appear to be vaccine-related.

Patient is a lovely 74-year-old female with a long history of PACs and hypertension.  Her blood pressure has been getting a little bit worse over the past years.  She was admitted through the ER with 1st known episode of atrial fibrillation and hypertension. She reports that on 02/02 she received her 2nd COVID vaccine.  She had joint achiness and a low-grade temperature.  She rested the following day but then on 02/04 went for her usual hour long runs/hike.  She did not feel very well during exercise and started have a headache and some increasing palpitations.  Later that evening she was watching TV and started to have significant tachycardia that was irregular. Symptoms persisted and she presented to the ER which sound to be in AFib with rapid ventricular response with a blood pressure of 215/158. She was started on a diltiazem drip and has converted to sinus rhythm with PACs.  Blood pressure has improved significantly.  Troponin negative x2.   Her last evaluation at a Heart facility was  in 2017.  She had an echocardiogram in 2014 with normal EF, mild MR and mild TR with normal estimated PA systolic pressure.   She denies chest pain or dyspnea.  No history of syncope.  Sometimes with palpitation she does get lightheaded.  She gets occasional lower extremity edema that seems dependent in nature.  She is still having palpitations but recognizes that she is no longer in atrial fibrillation as that was more severe in terms of symptoms of tachycardia.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: My first dose was 1/14. I found out I was pregnant on 1/26/21 and I miscarried at about 10 weeks. About 15 mins after I got the vaccine, I had a racing heartrate and my palms were hot, but it went away. Around 3pm, I had a right frontal headache. I took a nap and it went away. About 5am Fri, I woke up to severe arm pain and it felt like I was being stabbed in the stomach. I took about 400mg of Ibuprofen, went to sleep and was fine when I woke up. About 5pm Friday, I began having vaginal bleeding. I called my doctor and was able to get in on Feb 11th. At my OB/GYN appointment, they tested my blood and urine, which confirmed my pregnancy. The NP examined me and told me that the bleeding was coming from my cervix, so they sent me for an ultrasound the following week. That's when I was given my calculated date of 10 weeks. A gestational sac was observed, but they weren't sure if a fetus was present. I had to see my doctor every week since I was still bleeding and that continued until March 18th, when I lost the pregnancy completely. I took my specimen to the doctor the following day. They told me that they were sending it out to be tested, but I'm not sure if the results are back. They did confirm that it was a fetus.
LAB_DATA: Blood work - thyroid was abnormal. Was diagnosed with Hypothyroidism and my doctor doesn't know if it's related to the vaccine.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: This literature marketed report was received from the authors in a published literature article titled as stated above, regarding a 12-month-old female patient who, on an unknown date, when she was 9 months old, she experienced viral illness with prolonged febrile illness with seizures, triggered by seasonal coronavirus HKU1 infection. Later, when she was 10 months old, she experienced severe influenza A pneumonia with very high fever and progressive respiratory failure despite treatment with oseltamivir (dose, route and frequency not reported), ceftriaxone (dose, route and frequency not reported), methylprednisolone (dose, route and frequency not reported), and oxygen delivered by high-flow nasal cannula. She required intubation and mechanical ventilation for 3 days but recovered on an unknown date.  After that, on an unknown date, when she was 12 months old she was vaccinated with varicella virus vaccine live (oka/merck)(manufacturer unknown), along with measles, mumps, and rubella (wistar ra 27-3) virus vaccine, live (manufacturer unknown), hepatitis a vaccine, inactivated (manufacturer unknown), hib conj vaccine (unspecified carrier) and pneumococcal 13v conj vaccine (crm197) (administration routes, doses and frequencies were not reported), all of them for prophylaxis. It was mentioned that, during vaccination, the patient showed nasal congestion and clear rhinorrhea.  Then, 6 days after vaccinations, the patient presented with high fever, diarrhea, new onset vomiting, nasal congestion, cough, irritability, and lethargy.  On an unknown date, the patient was hospitalized. Then, a partial septic screen yielded above 100000 colony forming units/ml of Escherichia coli from her urine and a polymerase chain reaction (PCR) for rhinovirus/enterovirus RNA from a nasopharyngeal swab sample showed positive results. The patient's high fever continued despite intravenous ceftriaxone for presumed pyelonephritis, and she was on the pediatric ward for 2 days with continuing high fever up to 41�C.  On day 3, she was transferred to the Pediatric Intensive Care Unit (PICU) because of poor bilateral lower extremity perfusion that failed to improve on multiple fluid boluses. This was accompanied by persistent tachycardia, increased work of breathing, and a diffuse erythematous rash. On the 4th day after the onset of fever, she underwent several laboratory tests, which result were reported as follows: hemoglobin 12.1 g/dL (normal range between 10.2 to 14.7 g/dL); hematocrit of 34.4 percent (normal range between 30.8 to 43.7 percent); White blood cell count 7.6 x10x9/L (normal range between 6 to 17.5 x10x9/L); Absolute neutrophil count of 4 x10x9/L (normal range between 1.5 to 8.5 x10x9/L); Absolute lymphocyte count 2.3 x10x9/L (normal range between 4 to 10.5 x10x9/L(decreased)); Absolute monocyte count 1.2 x10x9/L (normal range between 0.3 to 0.9  x10x9/L (increased)); Platelet count 242 x10x9/L (normal range between 150 to 450 x10x9/L); aspartate aminotransferase (AST) 66 U/L (normal range between 10 to 37 U/L (increased)); alanine aminotransferase (ALT) 57 U/L (normal range between 5 to 30U/L (increased)). Also, a blood culture collected on day 4 and it was sterile.  On an unknown date, on the 6th day after the onset of fever, she underwent several laboratory tests, which result were reported as follows: hemoglobin 10.4 g/dL; hematocrit of 30.1 percent (decreased); White blood cell count 3.5 x10x9/L (decreased); Absolute neutrophil count of 2.2 x10x9/L; Absolute lymphocyte count 1 x10x9/L (decreased); Absolute monocyte count 0.2 x10x9/L (decreased)); Platelet count 144 x10x9/L (decreased); aspartate aminotransferase (AST) 57 U/L (increased); alanine aminotransferase (ALT) 38 U/L (increased); C-reactive protein 76 mg/dL (normal range between 0 to 0.8 mg/dL(increased)). Also, a blood culture was collected on day 6 and it was sterile. In addition, virology investigations were consistent with human herpes virus type 6 (HHV6) reactivation, based on positive blood PCR (23,500 (log 4.4) copies/ml of HHV-6 type B), positive HHV6 IgG at 1:80 (negative if below 1:10) and negative IgM (below 1:20) on day 6. On the 7th day after the onset of fever, she underwent several laboratory tests, which result were reported as follows: hemoglobin 10.1 g/dL (decreased); hematocrit of 29.2 percent (decreased); White blood cell count 2.3 x10x9/L (decreased); Absolute neutrophil count of 1.2 x10x9/L (decreased); Absolute lymphocyte count 1 x10x9/L (decreased); Absolute monocyte count 0.1 x10x9/L (decreased)); Platelet count 127 x10x9/L (decreased). On the 8th day after the onset of fever, she underwent several laboratory tests, which result were reported as follows: hemoglobin 9.4 g/dL (decreased); hematocrit of 26.9 percent (decreased); White blood cell count 1.4 x10x9/L (decreased); Absolute neutrophil count of 0.8 x10x9/L (decreased); Absolute lymphocyte count 0.6 x10x9/L (decreased); Absolute monocyte count 9.1 x10x9/L (increased)); Platelet count 107 x10x9/L (decreased). On the 9th day after the onset of fever, she underwent several laboratory tests, which result were reported as follows: hemoglobin 9.7 g/dL (decreased); hematocrit of 27 percent (decreased); White blood cell count 1.5 x10x9/L (decreased); Absolute neutrophil count of 0.8 x10x9/L (decreased); Absolute lymphocyte count 0.7 x10x9/L (decreased); Absolute monocyte count  0 x10x9/L (decreased)); Platelet count 85 x10x9/L (decreased); AST 221 U/L (increased); ALT 100 U/L (increased); Ferritin 1980 ng/dL (normal range between 12 to 207 ng/dL(increased)); Lactate dehydrogenase1043 U/L  (normal range between 190 to 420 U/L (increased)); Triglycerides 289 mg/dL (normal range between 30 to 120 mg/dL (increased)). An attempt at bone marrow aspiration on day 9 of admission was aborted due to apnea and profound desaturation. She was quickly resuscitated and returned to baseline within a few hours while hematologic parameters began spontaneously improving by day 10.  Also on 10th day after the onset of fever, she underwent several laboratory tests, which result were reported as follows: hemoglobin 9.8 g/dL (decreased); hematocrit of 26.3 percent (decreased); White blood cell count 2.7 x10x9/L (decreased); Absolute neutrophil count of 1.1 x10x9/L (decreased); Absolute lymphocyte count 1.3 x10x9/L (decreased); Absolute monocyte count  0.2 x10x9/L (decreased)); Platelet count 85 x10x9/L (decreased); AST 125 U/L (increased); ALT 94 U/L (increased); D-dimer above 9999 ng/ml (normal range between 0 to 499 (increased)); fibrinogen 71 mg/dL (normal range between 175 to 375 mg/dL (decreased)); Soluble interleukin-2 receptor 14740 pg/mL (normal range lower than 1034 (increased). Persistent high fever was accompanied by worsening cytopenia's, elevated triglycerides, elevated ferritin to equal or higher than 500 ng/ml, and elevated soluble interleukin-2 receptor level. These results met 5 of 8 criteria for the diagnosis of hemophagocytic lymph histiocytosis (HLH). Treatment with corticosteroids and other unspecified immunomodulators was planned after the bone marrow aspiration, but not administered because of clinical and laboratory evidence suggestive of spontaneous HLH resolution on day 10.  On the 11th day after the onset of fever, she underwent several laboratory tests, which result were reported as follows: hemoglobin 8.9 g/dL (decreased); hematocrit of 25.7 percent (decreased); White blood cell count 3.5 x10x9/L (decreased); Absolute neutrophil count of 1.4 x10x9/L (decreased); Absolute lymphocyte count 1.7 x10x9/L (decreased); Absolute monocyte count  0.3 x10x9/L; Platelet count 101 x10x9/L (decreased); AST 104 U/L (increased); ALT 85 U/L (increased); fibrinogen 65 mg/dL (decreased). On the 12th day after the onset of fever, she underwent several laboratory tests, which result were reported as follows: hemoglobin 8.1 g/dL (decreased); hematocrit of 24.5 percent (decreased); White blood cell count 5.6 x10x9/L (decreased); Absolute neutrophil count of 2.4 x10x9/L; Absolute lymphocyte count 2.6 x10x9/L (decreased); Absolute monocyte count  0.4 x10x9/L; Platelet count 135 x10x9/L (decreased); AST 82 U/L (increased); ALT 78 U/L (increased). On the 15th day after the onset of fever, she underwent several laboratory tests, which result were reported as follows: hemoglobin 8.9 g/dL (decreased); hematocrit of 27.3 percent (decreased); White blood cell count 9.1 x10x9/L; Absolute neutrophil count of 3.1 x10x9/L; Absolute lymphocyte count 24.6 x10x9/L; Absolute monocyte count 0.7 x10x9/L; Platelet count 534 x10x9/L (increased); AST 73 U/L (increased); ALT 55 U/L (increased). All the laboratory results were assessing as unremarkable. On an unknown date, the patient underwent ultrasonography, repeated plain x-radiography, contrast computerized tomogram (CT) and echocardiography which results showed no evidence of an infective focus in the renal tract, chest, abdomen/pelvis, or heart, respectively. The diagnosis was considered to be transient HLH triggered by HHV6 infection. Fever abated after 15 days and the child was discharged on no antibiotics.  On an unknown date, 20 days after vaccinations and immediately after hospital discharge, she developed a diffuse vesicular rash from which varicella-zoster virus (VZV) DNA was detected by PCR. The patient received treatment with acyclovir 20 mg/kg every 6 h, for 5 days, without complication.  The outcome of disseminated varicella zoster vaccine virus infection was reported as recovered. The reporter considered disseminated varicella zoster vaccine virus infection to be related to varicella virus vaccine live (Oka/Merck) (VARIVAX) as they considered tht it was more consistent with vaccine-strain varicella, than a wild type varicella.  Upon internal review, the event Disseminated varicella zoster vaccine virus infection was considered to be medically significant.  A copy of the published article is attached as further documentation of the patient's experience.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Client returned to LHD on 3/25/21 at 9:40am complaining of significant swelling into neck and axillary lymph nodes, redness, and difficulty moving arm. Redness was in an area over right deltoid approximately 4in vertically X 3 in horizontally. Redness did not go into shoulder, but started approximately 2 finger breaths below shoulder. Appeared vaccination was given in proper location. Client stated she was taking .Motrin and using the arm very frequently. She was tearful when moving arm.  Client feels her pain threshold is high due to hx of broken hip in past and this pain seems worse. Client was very concerned about a worse reaction with a second vaccine. Client did state, " the nurse said I was a really small person so she was going to use a smaller needle."  This nurse believes that means nurse at mass vaccination clinic used a 5/8 in needle. Client probably weighs 120-130lbs. Client did not and did not want to sign up for Vsafe. After discussion client decided to go to Urgent Care. Follow-up phone call to client  at 12:30pm on 3/26. Client states Urgent Care Dr did not think it was cellulitis. Client was very fatigued and stated she then went to daughters and took 2 hour nap. She felt she did not want to go home by self as she was still very concerned. Client states, 'has hx of developing significant tongue swelling throat closing reaction to Bactrim  about 4 days after starting and physician telling her in the ER she could have died if she did not come in'.  Advised her to get 2nd vaccine. Client is still undecided about getting 2nd vaccine. Pain has decreased, but arm remains swollen and is now itchy.  Client will continue to monitor and return to urgent care if symptoms get worse.
Left side felt numb and I was light headed

All of the reactions were red swollen, hot to touch area.The adverse reaction occurred in the left thigh; This spontaneous report has been received from an office manager concerning a child of unknown age and gender. The patient's concomitant therapies included sterile diluent (MERCK STERILE DILUENT). The patient's concurrent conditions, historical drugs and medical history were not reported.        On an unknown date, the patient was vaccinated with varicella virus vaccine live (oka/merck)(VARIVAX) 0.5 ml, subcutaneously, in the left thigh, Lot # T022314, expiration date 30-JUN-2022 for prophylaxis.     On an unknown date, the child experienced localized reactions. The patient had cellulitis at the shot location (Vaccination site cellulitis). All of the reactions were red swollen (Vaccination site swelling) and hot to touch area (Vaccination site warmth). The adverse reaction occurred in the left thigh; 4-6 centimeter wide.   It was reported that the patient sought medical attention and received treatment with antibiotics. It was unknown whether the patient underwent any laboratory or diagnostic tests.  The reporter informed that he/she has been doing this for 30 years and has never seen anything like it and he/she considered the reaction was coming from an specific lot number of varicella virus vaccine live (oka/merck)(VARIVAX) Lot # T022314, expiration date 30-JUN-2022. Additionally, that the adverse event was not related to the diluent because the same diluent was used for the Measles, Mumps, and Rubella (Wistar RA 27-3) Virus Vaccine, Live (M-M-R II) as was used for the varicella virus vaccine live (oka/merck)(VARIVAX)  and they had not had any adverse reactions involving the Measles, Mumps, and Rubella (Wistar RA 27-3) Virus Vaccine, Live (M-M-R II). The reporter informed they had 3 or 4 unused vials of the varicella virus vaccine live (oka/merck)(VARIVAX) Lot # T022314, expiration date 30-JUN-2022  left to return. It was reported that the varicella virus vaccine live (oka/merck)(VARIVAX) was stored at the recommended range, also reported as Frozen. It did not experience a temperature excursion and the storage temperature was monitored via a data logger. The reporter confirmed there were not any particles or matter in the varicella virus vaccine live (oka/merck)(VARIVAX) vial.  At the time of reporting, the patient was recovering from vaccination site cellulitis, vaccination site warmth and vaccination site swelling. The causal relationship between varicella virus vaccine live (oka/merck)(VARIVAX) and the vaccination site cellulitis, vaccination site warmth and vaccination site swelling was not reported. SYMPTOM_TEXT: Pasting clinicians note below: Patient is 61 year old female with hx of anaphylaxis presenting for Covid-19 vaccine, Dose #1.  She developed itching in there throat within 30 minute waiting period.    She was taken to Rapid Response Room.   Symptoms progressed from itchy throat, to congestion in throat/upper chest, clearing her throat, watery eyes.  Then dry cough.    No nausea, no vomiting, no light headed feeling.  No facial swelling  No hives.    OBJECTIVE: Vitals -  154/97, 105, 100%RA Neck -  Supraclavicular mild retractions, end inspiratory stridor CV: tachy, regular, no murmur pulm - diminished breathe sounds throughout, no wheezing.  Speaking full sentences.    Assessment/ Plan:   Anaphylaxis to Covid-19 Vaccine: -  emergency responders - epi 0.3 mg IM administered to L mid outer thigh at 9:35 am by me - epi 0.3 mg IM administered to R mid outer thigh at 9:41 am because symptoms not subsiding by me -benadryl 50 mg IM x 1 L deltoid by RN 9:45 am - Itching in throat subsided but still retracting and clearing throat so albuterol 3 puffs given at 9:50 am   Vitals stable entire time (see midas report)   EMS arrived to transport to local hospital.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: About 11:30 PM on 03/15/2021, started gasping for breath when laying down, sat up in lazy boy for a hour and half, beathing returned to normal.  About 3:30 PM on 3/16/2021, started gasping for breath again.  Called my daughter and she transported me to  Hospital.  They tested for covid - results negative.  They did a C-Scan of my chest and saw a blood clot in each lung.  While hooked to the monitors, they found I had Afib.  They also did an ultra-sound of my legs and found a small clot in each leg below the knees in a small vein.  I have never had any record of clots or Afib.  They transferred me to  Medical Center early on 3/17/2021.  They started a heparin drip to soften the clots.  In the afternoon of 3/17/2021, they performed a Suction Thrombectomy to remove the clots from my lungs.  On 3/19/2021, they put me on Eliquis Tab.  I was released from the hospital in the evening of 3/20/2021.

ED COURSE & MEDICAL DECISION MAKING Patient is a 20 y.o. male who presents emergency department for evaluation of fevers, chills, nausea, and shortness of breath.  Symptoms occurred approximately 3 to 4 hours after his Covid vaccination today.  He has not felt symptomatic for symptoms related to COVID-19 prior to his vaccination.  Nausea was noted without vomiting and he was given Zofran prior to arrival.  No objective evidence of anaphylaxis or angioedema was noted at urgent care nor was this noted on physical examination.  He does have a fever on arrival with Tylenol taken a little more then an hour prior to arrival.   Chest x-ray negative for findings of COVID-19.  There was no evidence of pneumonia.  His blood counts were otherwise reasonable though he did have relative lymphopenia that can be described in COVID-19 infection.  Metabolic profile was otherwise benign.  Differential diagnosis of his fever include the possibility of a vaccine reaction though the timing is rather quick for this reaction.  Certainly this remains in his differential.  His he has history of asthma and felt short of breath he was given Solu-Medrol.  He was given Toradol with improvement of symptoms as well as IV fluid.  With differential diagnostic considerations that he may have Covid, he was swabbed and tested at bedside.  With his well appearance he was ambulatory in the emergency department.  He was discharged stable condition with recommendations for Tylenol and ibuprofen in the short-term.     Procedures MDM     CHIEF COMPLAINT Fever and Chills     HPI The history is provided by the patient, medical records and the EMS personnel. Gradually over the weekend I felt my strength coming back and by Monday, I was much better.

Patient reported itching on arm first, then "all over" about 20 min after administration. She denied Benadryl due to extreme drowsiness. She did state that the itching "may be in my head". I watched her for 20 more minutes. She stated she is fine and good to leave. I asked her to call if anything outside of her normal happens.

She got the vaccine, and they asked her to stay for the 15 minutes and she was fine, but when she went out onto the street she started to have a few seconds of feeling faint but did not.  That feeling passed and was able to walk home and was getting vertigo.  She had a sore arm the next day, very fatigued and exhaustion.  Three days later had redness appear on the arm and then had headaches, and insomnia that night.  Her eyes were burning as well.  A day later had irregular heart beat and then six days later had the red line, raised in a circle that lasted one day.  She then continued to have the itching and then became a rash which was traveling under arm and onto her chest.  She then went to the city UC and was spreading to her breast, and started to subside.  Since then she has been having on and off headaches, on and off itching of both of her arms, as well as her scalp and other parts of her body.   As  a child had a history of hives.  When she went to the UC they did an EKG due to the irregular heart beat and did not want to go to the ER during the pandemic.  He gave her one Benadryl and 3 Ibuprofen which she only took one of, as she has a lot of allergies.  She has been taking Zyrtec 5 mg for the itching when she has it, which works for her.  The symptoms are subsiding, and has transient rashes on the vaccine arm, and on the right arm still have a few areas and still itching on and off.
PRIOR_VAX: both pneumonia and flu vaccines made her sick for a couple of days.  May have been sick from the first polio vaccine.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: On 3/1/2021, received second dose at 3:15pm and at 3:45pm driving home from work I developed chest pains and went to urgent care. I got there by 5:30pm and they ran an EKG; results were normal. On 3/2/2021, I left work at 2:30pm feeling ill and when I got home by 3:30pm I had flu symptoms. Symptoms were body aches, headache, fever, chills, nausea. This lasted for 24 hours. When I woke up on 3/4/2021, I was just tired with chest pains. I went to work and on my way home at 3:45pm shortness of breath started with increased chest pains. I went to urgent care and they told me to head to the ER. I got to the ER by 6pm. They ran blood work, EKG and Chest X-ray; results all normal. I followed up with PCP. I was out of work from 3/5/2021 to 3/12/2021. PCP thought I might have COVID. Took PCP test on 3/9 and results were negative. I was able to return to work on 3/15/2020 but still had shortness of breath and chest pains as well as feeling exhausted all the time. Due to no change, PCP provided me with script for Echocardiogram, Exercise Stress Test, inhaler as needed and to see Pulmologist.  Waiting on insurance company to approve echocardiogram and pulmologist appointment is 3/29/2021. It has been challenging to complete daily living activities like washing dishes, showering, climbing 20 stairs to my apartment, laundry, walking to the postal mailbox, etc. I get easily tired and winded. Prior to 3/1, I was healthy and exercising 3x's a week, walking 4 miles and hiked with no issues for the past year ranging 3.5-7 miles with incline.
LAB_DATA: 3/1/2021-EKG-normal 3/4/2021-EKG, Chest X-ray, bloodwork-all normal 3/9/2020- PCR nasal-negative and bloodwork for Mono-negative 3/17/2020-Biometric bloodwork-normal 3/17/2020-Inflammation bloodwork from Rheumotoligst (results high for inflammation) 3/26/2020-Exercise Stress Test complete 70% of test; had to stop test due to shortness of breath and chest pains
