Patient received her 1st dose of Moderna vaccine around 0845.  Patient was accompanied with her husband. They were leaving the facility and nurse noticed patient needed assistance walking, she went to assist her to the vehicle and when she was helping her the patient almost fell.  Nurse yelled for help, I assisted the patient to a chair outside the facility.  Vital signs were obtained:  BP 230/110 manual, Heart rate 110, 02 sat 95% on room air, Respirations 34.  Neuro exam completed, grips were equal and strong.  Patient was pale, diaphoretic, lethargic, and having shortness of breath.  Patient became very nauseated and started dry heaving.  History was obtained from the husband: HTN, COPD, Asthma, high cholesterol, anxiety, Chronic Back and Knee pain (currently seeing a pain clinic and is on Morphine 15mg q6 hours), wears 02 at bedtime.  Patient was assisted to an exam room via wheelchair.   Dr. was notified at 0924 of patient?s condition.  She informed me to call the emergency medical team to come assess her and transport to nearest hospital.   At 0925, 911 was notified.   Vital signs obtained: 0926:  BP 193/83, HR 114, Resp 38, 02 Sat 95% on room air. 0930:  Patient still having some shortness of breath, dry heaving, and nausea.  02 was placed at 2L BNC to assist with the shortness of breath.   0931:  BP 157/76, HR 102, 02 Sat 98% on 2L, Resp 32 0935:  1st responder arrived 0935:  BP 171/96, HR 99, 02 Sat 99% on 2L, Resp 30 0940:   Ambulance arrived to assess patient 0945:  EMS suggested to go to nearest hospital ER to be assessed by a doctor.  Patient and husband refused to be transported.  Patient?s husband stated, ?She has episodes like this all the time.?  He stated, ?I will take her to the ER if I feel that she needs to go.? 0955:  Ambulance crew left health department 0958:  Patient signed AMA form, patient left AMA with husband as driver.

He has not been any asthma medication for six years except 3-4 uses of albuterol during the fall Wildfire season. Vaccine lot numbers: 1st 041LZ0A, 2nd  003AQ1A. H ehad similar incident in 2012 after Reclast second dose. Had flushing first and then asthma flare. Lasted a couple weeks with just inhalers then had to do prednisone to calm it down. When tapered off he relapsed and had to do three iterations over a couple months.  After the second vaccine on Thursday AM, he was well until about 9PM that night, he developed sore throat and coughing that progressed through the night. On Friday AM he started using his nebulizer with albuterol and budesonide. His symptoms were manageable over the weekend. On Monday he coughed up a large collection of clear mucus and felt much better. On Wednesday 3/17, symptoms returned with cough and shortness of breath. He was started on a single dose of prednisone 40 mg and on Thursday he was seen in clinic. His symptoms seemed to be a mix of laryngeal and chest irritation. He was given an 8-day tapering course of prednisone and albuterol-ipratropium nebs every 6 hours. On follow up 3/25, he was much better except for side effects of the steroids. He is still being followed so I will provide updates if there is some change. He had a very similar reaction to Reclast in 2012 but has tolerated all other vaccines previously.
CUR_ILL: allergic rhinitis He had his allergy shot on 3/8/2021 three days prior to the second Moderna vaccine.
HISTORY: mild intermittent asthma, GERD, vocal cord dysfunction, osteoporosis

At approximately, 9:40 am I administered the Moderna Covid-19 vaccine with lot number: 020B21A with the expiration date 09/23/21 to a female patient. Approximately, 10 mins. into her waiting period the patient told me that she's experiencing rash which I witnessed on her chest area. At that time, I  asked did she have any difficulty breathing, tingling sensations around the face area, and any swelling of the face and tongue. She told me she was negative of the symptoms stated besides the rash. At approximately, 10:05 a.m. I gave the patient 10 mLs of liquid Benadry for a dose of 25 mg and I instructed the patient to wait another 5 to 10 minutes to see if symptoms persists and/or discontinue. I monitored the patient for an additional 15 mins and at that time I asked the patient how she's doing and she stated that  "the rash now traveled down to her legs". At that time I told the patient that I for your safety I'll have to administer a Epi-Pen injection. At that time, I let the store manager know of my intentions, instructed my technician to call 911, and administered one dose of the injection. I remained with the patient until EMS arrived at the scene.  According the patient she's had prior mild allergic reactions before, but nothing as serious as Penicillin. Overall, she seemed nervous during this time but was very understanding, calm and thankful that I remained with her.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I received the vaccine at 1:30 pm in the afternoon on 3/22/21 and immediately afterwards I felt fine. I waited my 15 minutes and had no signs of a reaction and was free to go. Later in the afternoon, around 3:15 pm, I began to feel a little fatigued and my arm was sore. Around 6:00 pm that same night, I developed a low grade temp of 99.8, I was very fatigued, had achiness all over, as well as my arm was very warm and tender.  I was unable to sleep through the night of 3/22/21 into 3/23/21 and got out of bed around 4: 30 am on 3/23/21 and had to call into work due to the pain. The pain was not an achiness but sharp throughout my whole body. Around 9:00 am, I took a pain reliever and was able to sleep for a few hours. Upon waking up around 1:30-2:00 pm, I was still hurting and was then nauseated as well. I tried to drink water and ate a few crackers to settle my stomach with no relief. At 5:15 pm on 3/23/21, I went to the bathroom and got in the shower to try to help with the pain. After a few minutes in the shower, I became extremely lightheaded and felt like I was going to be sick. I sat down in the bathtub and hollered for my mother to come help me because at this point, I felt like I needed to go to the hospital. Upon sitting down in the bathtub, I began to profusely vomit and started to lose feeling in my legs. My mother entered the bathroom and I explained what was happening and soon after my hands contracted and were stuck in an abnormal position. The pain was unbearable and I was unable to move them from that position. I was unable to get myself out of the bathtub so my mom then called for an ambulance. These symptoms occurred somewhere around 5:20-5:21 pm and EMS was called at 5:22 pm. After a few minutes, I was able to regain movement of my legs but my hands and fingers were still contracted and unmovable. I was able to help my mother enough to put my clothes on and to make my way outside to the front porch to get fresh air. After getting outside, I was accompanied by my mother and my neighbor whom is a nurse. My neighbor looked at my hands and noticed they were discolored and she attempted to straighten out my fingers to no avail. The pain in my fingers was sharp and excruciating but there was also a pins and needle type pain as well. I remained outside until EMS arrived. I was then transported to Hospital where I was seen in the ER for this. Upon arrival to the ER, the physician ordered labs and fluids and stated that apparently he had seen at least 2 other cases that day with a similar reaction to the vaccine. He explained that I was having an adverse reaction to the vaccine and that my hands should return to normal within 24-48 hours. I was then discharged home. As of 3/24/21, I was able to straighten my left hand out and my right hand, my fingers would straighten out, but they would return to a curled resting position. As of 3/25/21, I returned to work and I have some weakness in both hands with a slight discoloration of each hand as well. I am a nurse and work in an office and the physicians in my office commented on the color of skin upon seeing them. I was still very achy and fatigued. My arm was still sore and tender as well. As of today, 3/26/21, I am still achy as well as tired. My right hand has improved some but still returns to a curled resting position. The color of my hands has improved as well. I am a nurse and have seen many things throughout my career. This experience has been absolutely terrifying and I still have no answers as to why this happened to my body. I did my part by being vaccinated and was terrified that I was going to lose my life to it. I pray this does not happen to anyone else.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I had a severe migraine - and I don't have headaches. My whole face hurt.  (I have two optic aneurisms and I was afraid they were starting to bleed out.) My eye was running water even more at that point and I also had some mucus in my eye. I went to ER.  January 8 and they did a CT scan - and they gave me something IV for pain. They told me to take extra strength Tylenol every four hours and that didn't help. After one hour, I was in severe pain again. At that point, both eyes were tearing. I went to the dentist (Monday)  -and they did x-rays - (  to see if I had a tooth issue and I went to my ENT doctor  (Tuesday)- and he said it didn't appear that I had a major infection.  still in severe pain - she gave me a prescription to get rid of infection in my eyes. She gave me a steroid shot - which stopped the pain. The following week, I had an appt with an ophthalmologist- I was not in pain any more and my eyes had pretty much cleared up. He said I probably had a viral or bacterial infection prior and when I got the vaccine then that was why I got a migraine.  2nd vaccine - 30th of January (8:30) - I slept all that day - I was sleepy the whole day and the Sunday, I had flu like symptoms and after that I was fine. This week, I have the infection in my eyes again. I went back to the Dr yesterday to get an antibiotic because I was having the same kind of infections. This time - infection in my left eye, with tearing and mucus. They had me do the eye drops again and nasal spray I've been using.
LAB_DATA: CT scan - everything was normal - to make sure aneurisms were not bleeding - January 8 Dental x-rays - everything normal  - January 11 - everything normal
CUR_ILL: left eye started running water a lot - may have had some sinus issues
HISTORY: In Spring of 2020 - I had a heart stent put in.

I received an allergy immunotherapy shot the day before my first dose of the vaccine and instantly felt nauseous and extremely tired after receiving the vaccine, which continued for two days after receiving tut. Three days later, I woke up struggling to breathe (but not anaphylactic), covered in hives, itchy all over, shaking, disoriented, and chilled but not truly feverish.  I reported this to my allergist, who prescribed prednisone and suggested the vaccine combined with immunotherapy were too much for my immune system for one week. The hives, itchiness, and difficulty breathing lasted about four days. I struggled with fatigue and nausea for over two weeks, stopping all school and work in the meantime. After my second dose, I feel just a bit tired and sore, so I think this truly was a bad reaction to the two injections combined rather than to the vaccine itself. Still, it was a debilitating experience,  and I would recommend considering putting out guidance that other immunotherapy patients space out their allergy injections and vaccines farther than I did.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Multiple state agencies collaborated to provide the Moderna COVID-19 vaccine to the staff and the men and women in custody who work and reside in state correctional facilities. The mass vaccination process began on 02/17/2021.    Quality assurance processes in place for this vaccination effort identified two concerns regarding the vaccination process that occurred at seven facilities between the dates of 02/24/2021 and 03/05/2021.  Based on the information obtained, seven sites varied from the recommended best practices during the first round of vaccinations. A total of 5150 doses were provided to correctional staff and inmates in these seven facilities.    Our observations: o Based on our estimates of the number of doses per vial, it is possible that some recipients of the vaccine in these seven facilities may have received a lower than authorized dose of the vaccine.  o At two specific facilities, vaccine pooling did occur.  o There were no adverse outcomes reported from any of these facilities.   We gathered detailed information from all our vaccination sites.  We reviewed and analyzed this information and reported these observations to both Moderna, and to the agency. The conclusion of these meetings was that these variations in vaccine administration will have no impact on the vaccine's ability to provide protection and pose no ongoing risk to vaccine recipients.   We implemented the following modifications to improve our process: o Provided staff education regarding COVID-19 vaccination best practices o Established centralized dose preparation by health care staff at each facility o Included additional in-service dose preparation training for nursing staff by staff who were trained by Moderna o Initiated additional data collection by health care staff o Analyzed and monitored collected data to determine effectiveness of modifications   We will complete the required Vaccine Adverse Event Report (VAERs) to the agency.  We will provide notification to vaccine recipients at the seven facilities potentially impacted.

fever/temperature was 39.1 C; falls; her legs had given out from under her; multiple pulmonary nodules measuring up to 1.1 cm; systemic inflammatory response syndrome (SIRS); This is a literature report from the Elsevier, 2021, vol 397; pg. 1 (DOI: 10.1016/S0140-6736(21)00464-5) entitled "Fluorodeoxyglucose PET/CT findings in a systemic inflammatory response syndrome after COVID-19 vaccine".  A 65-year-old woman attended the hospital with a 1-day history of fever and falls, saying that her legs had given out from under her. The patient's symptoms began within 1 day of the first dose of the mRNA-1273 SARS-CoV-2 vaccine. She had a medical history of hypertension and diabetes. On examination in the emergency department, the patient's temperature was 39.1�C, her respiratory rate was 25 breaths per min, and her heart rate was 88 beats per min. As she met the criteria for systemic inflammatory response syndrome (SIRS), an extensive infection work-up was initiated and she was started on broad-spectrum antibiotics. Laboratory investigations found a D-dimer concentration of 5267 ng/mL, erythrocyte sedimentation rate of 69 mm/h, and a C-reactive protein concentration of 63.4 mg/L. The patient's white blood cell count, lactate, urinalysis, respiratory pathogen panel including SARS-CoV-2 and urine and blood cultures were unremarkable. Due to concerns of exposure to SARS-CoV-2, the PCR test was repeated after 24 h, but this was again negative. CT of the patient's chest showed multiple pulmonary nodules measuring up to 1.1 cm. A small filling defect in a distal subsegmental pulmonary artery was also seen, which the authors thought was inconsistent with an acute pulmonary embolism and probably artifactually. Doppler ultrasounds of the patient's lower limbs were normal; her head CT was also normal. 4 days after presentation, fluorodeoxyglucose (F-FDG) PET/CT was done to characterize the pulmonary nodules; it showed uptake in the fat stranding posterior to the right deltoid; moderately increased uptake within multiple right axillary lymph nodes; and diffusely increased splenic uptake. The pulmonary nodules had no uptake-indicating that they were probably benign. The patient's symptoms resolved 3 days after the vaccination. Given the imaging findings, the temporal relationship of the symptoms to the vaccination, and negative test results from an extensive work-up for malignant and infectious causes, the authors believe, the diagnosis was a local and systemic immune response following vaccination. However, possible masking effects of broad-spectrum antibiotics cannot be excluded. The high D-dimer concentration probably reflected significant concomitant coagulation and fibrinolysis associated with SIRS. The local response was demonstrated by hypermetabolism within the axillary lymph nodes draining the site of intramuscular injection; diffusely increased splenic activity suggests a systemic response- corroborated by elevated inflammatory markers. As the global vaccination effort continues, more patients will undoubtedly require assessment and investigation shortly after immunization. Imaging and laboratory findings consistent with a systemic immune response might result in further unnecessary evaluation or interventions. However, findings overlap with other diseases- notably those of the F-FDG PET/CT scan in patients with malignancies. Recognition of the clinical and imaging features of the systemic immune response to vaccination might become essential in the coming months.  No follow up attempts are needed. No further information is expected.; Sender's Comments: A causal association between BNT162B2 and the reported events cannot be excluded based on a compatible temporal relation. The impact of this report on the benefit/risk profile of the Pfizer product is evaluated as part of Pfizer procedures for safety evaluation, including the review and analysis of aggregate data for adverse events. Any safety concern identified as part of this review, as well as any appropriate action in response, will be promptly notified to RAs, Ethics Committees, and Investigators, as appropriate.

The following morning after I received my 2nd Moderna vaccine, I was awoken by my symptoms around 3:30am. My arm became so swollen and painful, I could not extend my arm at all.  I could only keep it bent and close to my body. I could not use my left arm at all for 2-3 days after the vaccine. The swelling got so bad that my entire arm felt numb and tingley and throbbed uncontrollably whenever I tried to move it.  I took ibuprofen and tylenol, every 6-7 hours as well as used warm and cold compresses, and that did nothing to help the swelling. The pain medications only took a slight edge off of the pain. I experienced these symptoms along with fever, body aches, muscle pain, joint pain, muscle spasms in my arm and leg muscles,  headache, and my nose was very runny after waking up in the morning.  All of those symptoms lasted for several days as well.  The numbness and pain lasted for a full week after the vaccine. It is now March 26th and my arm is still a bit sore at the vaccine site.  On Wednesday, March 24th, the vaccine site starting throbbing again and I did experience a low grade fever of 99.7 throughout the day. I felt very fatigued throughout the week as well.
LAB_DATA: None. But I did contact my doctor because I was so concerned that the vaccine administration may have hit a nerve or something based on the symptoms I was experiencing, but my doctor told me that the pain, numbness, and tingling was being caused by the swelling.
PRIOR_VAX: The first covid vaccine my arm was very sore afterwards as well.

On March 24, 2021, the day of the shot, I only felt soreness in my left arm. The next morning, March 25, 2021, I began to feel body aches, chills, and I was in a cold sweat. I took ibuprofen throughout the day to combat the symptoms. The evening of March 25, 2021, the pain was much more severe (body aches all over my body, including my face, teeth, my hands were sore and stiff, etc.). I did not sleep much of the night because the symptoms were very uncomfortable due to the chills and cold sweats. The morning of March 26, 2021, my left armpit began to swell. By the afternoon, my left armpit (the arm where I received the vaccine) was swollen, tender, and soft. There is some redness and the swelling and tenderness are more pervasive. It is difficult to hang my arm at my side due to the pain and swelling. I understand, after calling the nurse hotline, that this is a common side effect but I also have a skin condition (Hidradenitis Supparativa) and it is difficult to know whether flare-ups are triggered by environmental factors.
PRIOR_VAX: Anthrax - though not confirmed, I believe it caused a flare-up in my skin condition (Hidradenitis Supparativa)

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient received the COVID vaccine (Pfizer dose 1, Lot# ER8732, exp 7/31/2021) at 1316. Client reported ?my temperature is going up? at 1327. EMT and RN  responded. Client ambulated to the chair next to the EMT station with a steady gait. Client appeared flushed and diaphoretic. No complaints of shortness of breath, dizziness, numbness, or tingling. No appearance of hives or swelling. No loss of consciousness. Client has a history of multiple sclerosis and hypertention. Client was unaware of his baseline blood pressure ranges. Client takes no regular medications. The client has allergies to sulfa and seafood. At 1327, the client?s blood pressure was 140/110, with a pulse of 81, respiration rate of 18, and pulse oximeter reading of 98%. Eyes PERRLA, client was alert and oriented x4. Client was given orange juice and a bottle of water. The client reported not eating any food yet and only drinking some coffee and water before. Vital signs taken again at 1336, with a blood pressure of 150/110, 20 breaths per minute, heart rate 83, pulse oximeter reading 98%. At that time, the client?s color returned to normal and he was no longer diaphoretic. The client stated he felt ?much better.? Repeat blood pressure reading for the client at 1347 was 145/95. Final blood pressure reading for the client was 140/82 at 1352. The client stated he felt ?back to normal.? Education provided regarding emergency management and when to call 911. Client encouraged to follow up with his primary care provider within 24 hours. Client denied any further questions, was escorted to his car by EMT at 1357. The client left the facility with a steady gait and proceeded to drive himself home.

After the vaccine, did develop slight fever and flulike symptoms that lasted for ~24 hours and resolved.   She has received other vaccines before including flu, and childhood vaccines.  She is never had this type of reaction in the past. She states that her brothers, are describing similar reaction She is of Egyptian and Irish descent No family history of abnormal vaccine reactions.
